For a Giffen good,Income effect is positive and substitution effect is negative,Income effect is negative and substitution effect is positive,Income effect and substitution effect both are positive,Income effect and substitution effect both are negative,1,"AGiffen good: A good where higher price causes an increase in demand (reversing the usual law of demand). The increase in demand is due to the income effect of the higher price outweighing the substitution effect.
The concept of agiffen good is limited to very poor communities with a very limited choice of goods. Empirical evidence is hard to find, though some economists thought it applied to the Victorian poor who had very limited diet.
The idea is that if you are very poor and the price of your basic foodstuff (e.g bread) increases, then you cant afford the more expensive alternative food (meat) therefore, you end up buying more bread because it is the only thing you can afford.",Hint 187,1,1
